item.title: Spain's highest court suspends meeting of Catalonia's parliament
item.description: Spain's highest court has suspended a meeting of Catalonia's regional parliament planned for Monday in an apparent attempt to prevent Catalan President Carles Puigdemont's expected declaration of independence.

item.title: Hidden ballot boxes, encrypted texts
item.description: The images shocked Spain and reverberated around Europe. Officers with Spain's national security forces, in full riot gear, smashing their way into polling stations, dragging women out by the hair, and firing rubber bullets indiscriminately into crowds as they turned out to vote.

item.title: Independence vote caps four centuries of mistrust
item.description: The tensions laid bare between Catalonia and Spain's federal government over Sunday's referendum have a long and painful history that reaches back to the Franco era and beyond. But never since Spain became a democracy have relations been this polarized, the language so inflammatory.

item.title: Theresa May's nightmare speech
item.description: British Prime Minister Theresa May's attempt to relaunch her faltering premiership was badly derailed Wednesday when a keynote speech was marred by an interruption from a prankster, a prolonged coughing fit and finally the disintegration of the stage set behind her.

item.title: Probe asks: Who betrayed Anne Frank?
item.description: A new investigation into the circumstances surrounding the discovery of Anne Frank's hiding place in Nazi-occupied Amsterdam, which eventually led to her death, has been launched by a retired FBI agent.

item.title: Chemistry Nobel Prize for work in biomolecules
item.description: The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2017 has been awarded to three scientists for their pioneering work developing new methods of visualising biomolecules, such as the Zika virus.

item.title: Marseille knife attacker had 7 identities
item.description: A man who stabbed two women to death at a train station in the French city of Marseille on Sunday had several registered identities.

item.title: Pony Racing on the sands of the Emerald Isle
item.description: Most people go to the seaside to sit back, relax and get away from the rush of everyday life.

item.title: UK ex-PM child sex abuse claims substantiated
item.description: Police would have questioned former British Prime Minister Edward Heath over allegations of child sex abuse if he were still alive, an investigation has found.

item.title: Aung San Suu Kyi to be stripped of Oxford honor
item.description: Aung San Suu Kyi is to be stripped of the Freedom of Oxford by the city's council for her response to the Rohingya crisis.

item.title: UK to ban acid sales to minors
item.description: The UK government plans to ban the sale of acid to minors and prevent people from carrying corrosive liquids in public, in response to a dramatic increase in acid attacks across the country.

item.title: EU: Final warning for Facebook, Twitter
German president: New walls have gone up
item.description: Germany's president Frank-Walter Steinmeier has warned of the fractures in its society -- highlighted by the electoral success of the far-right party Alternative for Germany (AfD) -- on the nation's Day of German Unity.

item.title: New detectors reveal a cosmic calamity
item.description: With new gravitational wave detectors, scientists are able to observe black holes more closely, writes Don Lincoln.

item.title: Airline wants electric planes within a decade
Inside Denmark's giant LEGO house
item.description: Get ready to embrace your inner child at Denmark's new LEGO House -- a 12,000-square meter house of fun, filled with 25 million iconic colorful building blocks.

item.title: Frieze Week: Curator's picks for what to see outside the fair
item.description: Since its founding in 2003, Frieze London has transformed from an art world flyover fair, tucked away in Regent's Park, into an internationally recognized cultural event that engages galleries and museums -- and any other space that can repurposed to showcase art -- across the city.

item.title: How London is capital for acid attacks on youth

item.description: "I am sure the surgery will solve the problem, but it is unlikely he will ever be any good at sports."

item.title: The surfer with a fear of rocks and underwater
item.description: The Portuguese surfer had an abject terror of rocks as a child and even now has a phobia of being underwater, which makes his career choice all the more remarkable.

item.title: Finding grandpa's photos: a quest
Barca's Pique not going to retire
Recapturing travel magic in Italy
Gene Simmons on Prince: He 'did it all'
item.description: KISS bassist Gene Simmons speaks to CNN's Pamela Brown about his immense respect for Prince.

item.title: Mysterious fireball lights up night sky
item.description: A bright glowing object, believed to be a meteor, flashed through the atmosphere above northeast Scotland, lighting the night sky and startling residents.

item.title: The crystal Bible to last a billion years
item.description: Researchers in the U.K. have developed digital data discs that can survive possibly longer than the human race.

item.title: Cricket spaghetti sold in France
item.description: This business in northeastern France is making pasta out of creepy crawlies.

item.title: What is the European Union?
item.description: CNN's Max Foster explains the origins and founding philosophy of the European Union.

item.title: 500-year-old shipwreck emerges from river
item.description: A 15th century merchant ship has been raised from a riverbed in the Netherlands.

item.title: Jews leave France in record numbers
item.description: New data from Israel shows that a record number of French Jews have left France in the twelve months since the Charlie Hebdo attacks.
